KEY: With S(1,N) = M(N)+1, the m=1 change at prime p is:

  |S(1,p)|² = (M(p)+1)²
  |S(1,p-1)|² = (M(p-1)+1)² = (M(p)+2)²

  Δ|S(1)|² = (M(p)+1)² - (M(p)+2)² = -2M(p) - 3

  For M(p) ≤ -3: Δ|S(1)|² = -2M(p)-3 ≥ -2(-3)-3 = 3 > 0

  So |S(1,p)|² > |S(1,p-1)|² when M(p) ≤ -3.
  The m=1 Parseval term INCREASES at p.

  Meanwhile for the cross-term in δΣ:
  m=1: 2·Re(S(1,p-1))·c_p(1) + c_p(1)² = 2(M(p)+2)(-1) + 1
      = -2M(p) - 4 + 1 = -2M(p) - 3
  For M(p) ≤ -3: this ≥ 3 > 0.  GOOD — drives δΣ positive!

