==============================================================================
PROOF ARGUMENT SUMMARY
==============================================================================

Identity: S(m,N) = 1 + Σ_{q=1}^N c_q(m), where c_q(m) is Ramanujan sum.
For m=1: S(1,N) = M(N) + 1.

At prime p: S(m,p) = S(m,p-1) + c_p(m)
  c_p(m) = -1   if p ∤ m
  c_p(m) = p-1   if p | m

Change in |S(m)|²:
  Δ|S(m)|² = 2·Re(S(m,p-1))·c_p(m) + c_p(m)²

For m=1:
  Δ|S(1)|² = 2(M(p)+2)(-1) + 1 = -2M(p) - 3
  When M(p) ≤ -3: Δ|S(1)|² ≥ 3

This means the m=1 Parseval term INCREASES at p,
driving W(p) > W(p-1) would be wrong — we need to account
for the normalization 1/n changing too.

The balance is: ΔW < 0 iff the 'energy injection' δΣ
outpaces the 'dilution' from n growing by p-1.

When M(p) ≤ -3, the m=1 injection -2M(p)-3 ≥ 3 is large
enough (combined with positive diagonal terms) to overcome
the dilution for all tested primes.

