==============================================================================
FINAL SUMMARY OF FINDINGS
==============================================================================

ESTABLISHED IDENTITIES:
  1. S(m,N) = 1 + Σ_{q=1}^N c_q(m)  [Ramanujan sum decomposition]
  2. S(1,N) = M(N) + 1               [Mertens function + boundary]
  3. c_p(m) = -1 if p∤m, p-1 if p|m  [prime Ramanujan sums]
  4. δΣ_diag = π²(p-1)/(3p)          [EXACT, verified]
  5. Δ|S(1)|² = -2M(p)-3             [EXACT, verified]

KEY STRUCTURAL RESULT:
  ΔW = C · [(p-1)·Σ₁ - n₁·δΣ] / (n₁·n₂)
  ΔW < 0  iff  n₁·δΣ > (p-1)·Σ₁
  iff  [n₁/(p-1)] · [δΣ/Σ₁] > 1

  Factor 1: n₁/(p-1) ~ 3p/π² → grows linearly in p
  Factor 2: δΣ/Σ₁ stays O(1), bounded below for M(p)≤-3

WHY M(p) ≤ -3 MATTERS:
  The m=1 term of δΣ is -2M(p)-3.
  For M(p) ≤ -3: this term ≥ 3, providing a LARGE positive
  injection into δΣ that makes δΣ/Σ₁ large enough that
  [n₁/(p-1)] · [δΣ/Σ₁] > 1 for ALL tested primes.

CROSS-TERM STRUCTURE:
  - The p∤m cross terms = -2·Σ Re(S(m,p-1))/m²
    These are POSITIVE (because Re(S(m,N)) < 0 on average
    for m≥2, analogous to M(N) < 0 for m=1)
  - The negative contributions to cross_rest are BOUNDED
    (numerically ≈ -1 to -2, independent of p)
  - The positive contributions GROW with p

PROOF STATUS:
  - Verified ΔW(p) < 0 for ALL primes with M(p)≤-3 up to p=47
  - The ET ratio is always ≥ 2.0 for M(p)≤-3 (safety margin!)
  - Cauchy-Schwarz alone is too loose to close the proof
  - Need a SHARPER bound on cross_rest, e.g., using the fact
    that Σ Re(S(m,N))/m² is negative on average (like Mertens)
  - The growth rate argument (n₁/(p-1) → ∞) means the proof
    only needs to work for finitely many small primes
